Issues.Body:
## 🚨 Bug: Controls change `Width` after Ctrl+C/Ctrl+V when width is not fixed inside containers

### Description

In Windows Forms (.NET 5 through 9), any control **without a manually fixed `Width`** placed inside containers (`GroupBox`, `Panel`, `TabPage`, etc.) can have its **width automatically changed** when performing:

- **Ctrl + C** (copy)
- **Ctrl + V** (paste)
- Copy/paste operations in the Designer with `UserControls`
- Sometimes even just focusing or interacting with the control via keyboard

This bug affects various controls, including:

- `TextBox`
- `RichTextBox`
- `ComboBox`
- `UserControl`
- And other standard or custom controls

---

### ✅ Expected behavior

Controls **should maintain their stable width**, as happens in .NET Framework, even after copy/paste operations or keyboard interactions.

---

### ❌ Actual behavior

The control's `Width` is **automatically changed**, without any developer intervention, breaking the visual layout.

---

### ✅ How to reproduce

1. Create a new **Windows Forms App** project (.NET 5 through 9)
2. Add a `GroupBox` or `Panel`
3. Inside it, add any control such as a `TextBox` **without setting a fixed width**
4. Run the application
5. Type something and press **Ctrl + C** (or use Ctrl + V)
6. Observe the control changing its size

### 🧪 Environment

- **.NET SDK**: 9.0.301  
  (Issue also confirmed in .NET 5, 6, 7, 8)  
- **Operating System**: Windows 11 Home 24H2 (Build 26100.4484)  
- **IDE**: Visual Studio 2022 and 2025 Preview  
- **Project Type**: Windows Forms Application  

#### Minimal example code:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Windows.Forms;

namespace WinFormsWidthBug
{
    public class MainForm : Form
    {
        public MainForm()
        {
            var groupBox = new GroupBox
            {
                Text = "Container",
                Width = 300,
                Height = 100,
                Left = 10,
                Top = 10
            };

            var textBox = new TextBox
            {
                Left = 10,
                Top = 30,
                Anchor = AnchorStyles.Left | AnchorStyles.Top,
                // Width is not fixed here!
            };

            groupBox.Controls.Add(textBox);
            Controls.Add(groupBox);

            Text = ".NET Width Bug";
            Width = 400;
            Height = 200;
        }

        [STAThread]
        public static void Main()
        {
            Application.EnableVisualStyles();
            Application.Run(new MainForm());
        }
    }
}

### .NET version

Every version is affected

### Did it work in .NET Framework?

No

In .NET Framework the same issue exists. The only difference that it causes an `AccessViolationException` rather than an `ExecutionEngineException`. I think I've found the same issue reported [here](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-ie/answers/questions/2124572/why-am-i-encountering-a-system-accessviolationexce), but they couldn't provide a reproduction.

### Issue description

Changing the `RightToLeft` property of the `Form` triggered by the `SelectedValueChanged` event of a `ComboBox` may lead to an `ExecutionEngineException` (.NET Framework: `AccessViolationException`).

The exception does not always occur for the first time, but after a few tries it happens eventually.

Though I haven't performed a deep analysis, the issue may have something to do with the fact that changing `Form.RightToLeft` recreates the whole form, and if it happens when the combo box was dropped down, some Windows messages may be processed on an already freed handle.

### Steps to reproduce

A minimal repro:

**ExceptionFromComboBox.cs:**
```cs
using System;
using System.Windows.Forms;

namespace WindowsFormsApp1
{
    public partial class ExceptionFromComboBox : Form
    {
        public ExceptionFromComboBox()
        {
            InitializeComponent();
            cmbRtl.ComboBox.DataSource = new[] { RightToLeft.No, RightToLeft.Yes };
            cmbRtl.ComboBox.SelectedValueChanged += ComboBox_SelectedValueChanged;
        }

        private void ComboBox_SelectedValueChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
        {
            RightToLeft = (RightToLeft)cmbRtl.ComboBox.SelectedValue;
        }
    }
}
```

